title: Added optional file compression, optional keeping of flags
body:
Hey,

I added two new arguments to the `get_eurostat`-function:
- one to enable compressing of the .rds-file: `compress_file`
- one to keep flags and save them in a separate column, instead of just removing them: `keepFlags`

Compressing can make quite a difference: 260MB vs 2.8MB (with `stringsAsFactors = TRUE`) and 538MB vs 4.2MB (with `stringsAsFactors = FALSE`) for the supply tables data `naio_10_cp15` (tested on both Windows and Linux).

To extract the flags, I just use a simple character extraction. I use a function from the _stringi_ package to extract the flags from the `value`-column (this package is imported by the `tidyr` package anyway, but I added it to the Suggests-list in the Description). I set the default to FALSE, so as to maintain backwards compatibility.

title: eurotime2date: avoid warning when time variable is a year interval
body:
Hi,

This is a tiny bugfix for `eurotime2date.R` that avoids printing a warning when the `time` variable of a dataset is a year interval of the form `2006_2008`. The code now simply skips it.

Perhaps the same kind of fix should be applied to `eurotime2num.R` too.

title: URL-s update for bulk downloading
body: As @jhuovari wrote #13, URL for bulk downloading changed (and broke a project I was working on). Updated the URL for both getEurostatDictionary and get_eurostat_raw.

title: get_eurostat to use cache
body: Now `get_eurostat` calls `get_eurostat_raw` to get data and `tidy_eurostat` to format the data. By default it cache the data.frame to temp directory. The cache directory can also be specified with an argument or an option. Updating the data can also be done an argument or an option.

title: tidyr version of the getEurostatRaw
body:
I just noticed extract_numeric in tidyr and couldn't resist. It's faster than original.

Other comments: I think header = F in read.table and then manually giving column names that are not legal column names is not good idea. Better change them in getEurostatRCV. And mayby change them to dates? Or at least option to change them to dates?

title: First version of getEurostatRCV with tidyr
body:
Rewrote getEurostatRCV with tidyr

I tried a new tidyr package for getEurostatRCV and replaced the previously used melt from 
reshape package. The speed improved is sizable. With “avia_goincc” data the system.time() gives 
with reshape:
   user  system elapsed 
  59.52   10.15   70.41

with tidyr:
   user  system elapsed 
   0.05    0.00    0.05 

Improved is probably due to dplyr that tidyr uses. Could be used also to getEurostatRaw?

The data.frame that the modified function returns is bit different from previous version. Variable columns 
no longer have (row)names. It think that was duplication of information and output of str() from 
that data.frame was confusing and hard to read.

Ideas:
getEurostatRCV is long and hard to remember. Better get_eurostat and make getEurostatRaw internal? 
or only eurostat and remove existing eurostat-function? is stat fin version really needed?

If you accept the idea on using tidyr, mayby you should anyway merge it to some development branch, as modification will change the return value and is not tested that much.

title: Add new functions to work with Eurostat codes and labels/definitions
body:
Add new functions to work with Eurostat codes and labels/definitions
The function label_eurostat takes Eurostat codes and turn them to 
labels with getEurostatDictionary. label_eurostat_vars and 
label_eurostat_tables are special cases for variable names and 
table names.

Handy for example when plotting.

Issues:
- Now uses mapvalue from plyr. Could be implemented also without.
- Naming. I tried to follow Hadley’s style guide as advised in rOpenGov 
  guidelines. Other functions in package are however in camelCase.
  Should I change?
- Documenting is still minimal.
